article.description: The Orlando Miracle needed help if they were to reach the playoffs. They didn't get it.
article.headline: Miracle don't get help in playoff push
article.linkText: Miracle victory over Liberty ends up hollow
article.story: ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Miracle needed help if they were to reach the playoffs. They didn't get it. Orlando beat the New York Liberty 70-63 in the season finale Tuesday night, but Indiana clinched the final Eastern Conference postseason berth by beating Cleveland. Orlando matched Indiana at 16-16, but the Fever owned the tiebreaker through their 2-1 edge in the season series. "Thinking back to the games where where we didn't play as well as we wanted to, let some games slip,'' said Shannon Johnson, who led Orlando with 14 points and seven rebounds. "It hurts more right now because you look back at that and one or two games here, and we would be in the playoffs right now and it would be a different story.'' Wendy Palmer added 12 points and seven rebounds for the Miracle, and Nykesha Sales had 10 points and a career-high eight rebounds. The Miracle and their fans were never told of their dashed playoff hopes because coach Dee Brown forbid the arena announcer from revealing the Fever-Rockers score. But not long after Indiana won, downcast faces were seen on the Orlando bench. "It was sad,'' Sales said of hearing the score midway through the second half. "We still wanted to end the season on a high note and win, but it's unfortunate that we couldn't make the playoffs.'' The Liberty (18-14), the East's top seed despite losing four of their last five games, will face the Fever in the first round of the playoffs. "We had nothing to play for the last six games and that makes it tough,'' New York coach Richie Adubato said. "We'll be fine in the playoffs.'' Tari Phillips led New York with 20 points and 10 rebounds, and Tamika Whitmore had 20 points and seven rebounds. Johnson continued her domination of the Liberty, who have lost five straight to Orlando. In the Miracle's three wins, Johnson averaged 18.7 points, 6.0 rebounds and 4.7 assists. After a tentative start, the Miracle took control late in the first half behind a 23-6 run. Johnson's drives into the paint led the charge, and she scored all 12 of her first-half points in a 5:31 span as Orlando took a 33-22 lead . But the Liberty rallied with a 10-0 run in little more than a minute when Orlando turned the ball over on three straight possessions. That comeback prompted Adubato to keep his starters in, despite the Liberty having nothing to play for. "I left the players in long because after Orlando got the big lead, we came back,'' he said. "I felt I owed it to the team to give them a chance to win.'' The Liberty tied it at 39 early in the second half, only to let Orlando get ahead for good behind a 10-0 run. Palmer and Hicks each had four points to help the Miracle pull away.
